{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HjjmXQceHASaUyBKEY3hrx","type":"tool_result","content":"Sheet name: Methodology\nRange: A1:A28\nA1: \"Please provide a brief explanation for how you approached working through this.\\r\\n(what was your methodology, prompt(s), tools, etc)\"\nA3: \"APPROACH:\"\nA4: \"  • Structured the analysis end to end across 16 sequential steps, from workbook inspection through to executive memo generation\"\nA5: \"  • Reviewed the full vendor dataset to understand spend distribution, identify the top-10 vendors by spend, and quantify long-tail exposure\"\nA6: \"  • Identified workbook structure and template constraints upfront — including allowed departments, recommendation values, and cell-level write rules — before writing any data\"\nA7: \"  • Sequenced the analysis in four logical phases: inspection and data understanding → vendor classification and categorisation → opportunity identification and prioritisation → recommendations and documentation\"\nA9: \"METHODOLOGY:\"\nA10: \"  • Data review: vendor spend data sourced directly from workbook; total spend and concentration analysed across all 386 vendors\"\nA11: \"  • Spend concentration analysis: top 10 vendors ranked by spend, accounting for the majority of total outlay; long-tail vendors below $50K identified for rationalisation\"\nA12: \"  • Vendor categorisation: service categories and departments assigned to each vendor using domain knowledge and spend pattern analysis\"\nA13: \"  • Service overlap identification: duplicate service categories detected across vendors; consolidation candidates flagged for further evaluation\"\nA14: \"  • Cost optimisation framework: Terminate / Consolidate / Optimize decision rules applied per vendor based on strategic value, spend level, and category overlap\"\nA15: \"  • Opportunity prioritisation: top 3 opportunities selected using multi-factor evaluation across financial impact, execution effort, business risk, and time to value\"\nA17: \"PROMPTS:\"\nA18: \"  • A 16-step structured prompt workflow was designed and executed sequentially via Claude Code CLI\"\nA19: \"  • Each step had a single clearly scoped analytical task: inspect, classify, score, identify, validate, or document\"\nA20: \"  • Key prompts covered: workbook inspection, vendor classification, duplicate detection, strategic scoring, opportunity identification, methodology documentation, and executive memo generation\"\nA21: \"  • All prompts enforced strict output format rules: allowed departments, recommendation values, cell-level write constraints, and sheet-level write guards\"\nA22: \"  • Prompts were passed to Claude Code CLI via stdin pipe in non-interactive mode using printf\"\nA24: \"TOOLS:\"\nA25: \"  • Claude Code CLI (Anthropic): AI reasoning and analytical tasks across all 16 steps\"\nA26: \"  • Node.js with xlsx (SheetJS) library: Excel workbook read and write operations throughout the pipeline\"\nA27: \"  • Python with openpyxl: post-pipeline formatting restoration from the original template to preserve visual structure\"\nA28: \"  • Bash orchestration script: step sequencing, checkpoint and resume logic, and log capture across all pipeline stages\"","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_016z3yMxPR2WwAu4VkD717sf","session_id":"4a5998dc-503b-4df4-b16c-7a512e7e5d41","uuid":"2bc5e839-097d-4b88-a67b-7a3cb73c8a40","timestamp":"2026-03-22T16:37:28.634Z"}
