{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016z3yMxPR2WwAu4VkD717sf","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the full output from the script:\n\n---\n\n**Sheet name:** `Methodology`\n**Range:** `A1:A28` (single column, 28 rows)\n\n---\n\n**Cell A1 — Template instruction:**\n> \"Please provide a brief explanation for how you approached working through this. (what was your methodology, prompt(s), tools, etc)\"\n\n---\n\n**All non-empty cells:**\n\n| Cell | Value |\n|------|-------|\n| A1 | *(template instruction — see above)* |\n| A3 | `APPROACH:` |\n| A4 | Structured the analysis end to end across 16 sequential steps, from workbook inspection through to executive memo generation |\n| A5 | Reviewed the full vendor dataset to understand spend distribution, identify the top-10 vendors by spend, and quantify long-tail exposure |\n| A6 | Identified workbook structure and template constraints upfront — including allowed departments, recommendation values, and cell-level write rules — before writing any data |\n| A7 | Sequenced the analysis in four logical phases: inspection and data understanding → vendor classification and categorisation → opportunity identification and prioritisation → recommendations and documentation |\n| A9 | `METHODOLOGY:` |\n| A10 | Data review: vendor spend data sourced directly from workbook; total spend and concentration analysed across all 386 vendors |\n| A11 | Spend concentration analysis: top 10 vendors ranked by spend; long-tail vendors below $50K identified for rationalisation |\n| A12 | Vendor categorisation: service categories and departments assigned using domain knowledge and spend pattern analysis |\n| A13 | Service overlap identification: duplicate service categories detected; consolidation candidates flagged |\n| A14 | Cost optimisation framework: Terminate / Consolidate / Optimize decision rules applied per vendor based on strategic value, spend level, and category overlap |\n| A15 | Opportunity prioritisation: top 3 opportunities selected using multi-factor evaluation across financial impact, execution effort, business risk, and time to value |\n| A17 | `PROMPTS:` |\n| A18 | A 16-step structured prompt workflow was designed and executed sequentially via Claude Code CLI |\n| A19 | Each step had a single clearly scoped analytical task: inspect, classify, score, identify, validate, or document |\n| A20 | Key prompts covered: workbook inspection, vendor classification, duplicate detection, strategic scoring, opportunity identification, methodology documentation, and executive memo generation |\n| A21 | All prompts enforced strict output format rules: allowed departments, recommendation values, cell-level write constraints, and sheet-level write guards |\n| A22 | Prompts were passed to Claude Code CLI via stdin pipe in non-interactive mode using `printf` |\n| A24 | `TOOLS:` |\n| A25 | Claude Code CLI (Anthropic): AI reasoning and analytical tasks across all 16 steps |\n| A26 | Node.js with xlsx (SheetJS) library: Excel workbook read and write operations throughout the pipeline |\n| A27 | Python with openpyxl: post-pipeline formatting restoration from the original template |\n| A28 | Bash orchestration script: step sequencing, checkpoint and resume logic, and log capture across all pipeline stages |\n\n---\n\n**Sheet dimensions:** Single column A, rows 1–28. All content is in column A only — no other columns contain data. Empty rows at A2, A8, A16, and A23 serve as section separators between the four sections (Approach, Methodology, Prompts, Tools)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: afd37e0f8a645629f (use SendMessage with to: 'afd37e0f8a645629f' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 11207\ntool_uses: 3\nduration_ms: 24361</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4a5998dc-503b-4df4-b16c-7a512e7e5d41","uuid":"512b8b90-0e62-4e1f-9515-6e386dd62d64","timestamp":"2026-03-22T16:37:38.749Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Read the Methodology sheet from the Excel workbook at C:/Users/rjega/vendor-spend-analysis/outputs/A - TEMPLATE - RWA - Vendor Spend Strategy (R Jegadeswari).xlsx\n\nWrite a Node.js script to read this sheet and output:\n1. The value of cell A1 (template instructions)\n2. All non-empty cells with their addresses and values\n3. The sheet dimensions\n\nRun the script and return the full output.\n\nUse this script:\n```javascript\nconst XLSX = require('xlsx');\nconst path = require('path');\n\nconst filePath = 'C:/Users/rjega/vendor-spend-analysis/outputs/A - TEMPLATE - RWA - Vendor Spend Strategy (R Jegadeswari).xlsx';\nconst wb = XLSX.readFile(filePath);\n\nconst sheetName = wb.SheetNames.find(n => n.toLowerCase().includes('method'));\nconsole.log('Sheet name:', sheetName);\n\nconst ws = wb.Sheets[sheetName];\nconst range = ws['!ref'];\nconsole.log('Range:', range);\n\n// Print all non-empty cells\nconst decoded = XLSX.utils.decode_range(range);\nfor (let r = decoded.s.r; r <= decoded.e.r; r++) {\n  for (let c = decoded.s.c; c <= decoded.e.c; c++) {\n    const addr = XLSX.utils.encode_cell({r, c});\n    const cell = ws[addr];\n    if (cell && cell.v !== undefined && cell.v !== '') {\n      console.log(`${addr}: ${JSON.stringify(cell.v)}`);\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSave it to C:/Users/rjega/vendor-spend-analysis/read_methodology.js, run it with node, and return the full output.","agentId":"afd37e0f8a645629f","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the full output from the script:\n\n---\n\n**Sheet name:** `Methodology`\n**Range:** `A1:A28` (single column, 28 rows)\n\n---\n\n**Cell A1 — Template instruction:**\n> \"Please provide a brief explanation for how you approached working through this. (what was your methodology, prompt(s), tools, etc)\"\n\n---\n\n**All non-empty cells:**\n\n| Cell | Value |\n|------|-------|\n| A1 | *(template instruction — see above)* |\n| A3 | `APPROACH:` |\n| A4 | Structured the analysis end to end across 16 sequential steps, from workbook inspection through to executive memo generation |\n| A5 | Reviewed the full vendor dataset to understand spend distribution, identify the top-10 vendors by spend, and quantify long-tail exposure |\n| A6 | Identified workbook structure and template constraints upfront — including allowed departments, recommendation values, and cell-level write rules — before writing any data |\n| A7 | Sequenced the analysis in four logical phases: inspection and data understanding → vendor classification and categorisation → opportunity identification and prioritisation → recommendations and documentation |\n| A9 | `METHODOLOGY:` |\n| A10 | Data review: vendor spend data sourced directly from workbook; total spend and concentration analysed across all 386 vendors |\n| A11 | Spend concentration analysis: top 10 vendors ranked by spend; long-tail vendors below $50K identified for rationalisation |\n| A12 | Vendor categorisation: service categories and departments assigned using domain knowledge and spend pattern analysis |\n| A13 | Service overlap identification: duplicate service categories detected; consolidation candidates flagged |\n| A14 | Cost optimisation framework: Terminate / Consolidate / Optimize decision rules applied per vendor based on strategic value, spend level, and category overlap |\n| A15 | Opportunity prioritisation: top 3 opportunities selected using multi-factor evaluation across financial impact, execution effort, business risk, and time to value |\n| A17 | `PROMPTS:` |\n| A18 | A 16-step structured prompt workflow was designed and executed sequentially via Claude Code CLI |\n| A19 | Each step had a single clearly scoped analytical task: inspect, classify, score, identify, validate, or document |\n| A20 | Key prompts covered: workbook inspection, vendor classification, duplicate detection, strategic scoring, opportunity identification, methodology documentation, and executive memo generation |\n| A21 | All prompts enforced strict output format rules: allowed departments, recommendation values, cell-level write constraints, and sheet-level write guards |\n| A22 | Prompts were passed to Claude Code CLI via stdin pipe in non-interactive mode using `printf` |\n| A24 | `TOOLS:` |\n| A25 | Claude Code CLI (Anthropic): AI reasoning and analytical tasks across all 16 steps |\n| A26 | Node.js with xlsx (SheetJS) library: Excel workbook read and write operations throughout the pipeline |\n| A27 | Python with openpyxl: post-pipeline formatting restoration from the original template |\n| A28 | Bash orchestration script: step sequencing, checkpoint and resume logic, and log capture across all pipeline stages |\n\n---\n\n**Sheet dimensions:** Single column A, rows 1–28. All content is in column A only — no other columns contain data. Empty rows at A2, A8, A16, and A23 serve as section separators between the four sections (Approach, Methodology, Prompts, Tools)."}],"totalDurationMs":24361,"totalTokens":11207,"totalToolUseCount":3,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":810,"cache_read_input_tokens":9571,"output_tokens":825,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":810},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
